commit.message: Bump version to 0.9.24.

Update GitHub workflow configurations

Update actions to run on pull requests as well as main.
Update the actions to their latest versions.
Skip the dev environment setup as it isn't currently needed.
Bump version to v0.9.23.

Add pylint-3.1 code back in.

This re-adds the pylintrc and the `run lint` command so
that we can still run `pylint` (in addition to being able to run
`ruff check`.
Tweak two tests that somehow got dropped in the merges.

Add additional tests and simplify dead code.

This change adds a bunch of additional tests for error and
corner cases, and either deletes dead code or annotates it
as dead.

With these changes the tests should achieve 100% code coverage.
remove hypothesis tests

Reformat the code with Ruff (`./run format`).

This reformats all the code with the Ruff Python formatter.
pyproject.toml contains the configuration for the formatter.

Get things linting again.

Linted against pylint 3.11 with the pylintrc
file recommended from the Google Python Style Guide,
specifically from
https://github.com/google/styleguide/blob/28d10d1/pylintrc.

Then ran through `ruff check` as well.
one more thing in run
remove a couple more py2-isms

Remove python2-isms.

This removes all of the Python2-compatibility code in the
package, mostly `u''` string declarations, but a few other
things as well.

Attempt to fix the GitHub CI configuration.

Removing setup.py broke the GitHub CI configuration. This
change should fix that, and also changes things so that we
test on 3.12 instead of 3.11.
bump version to 0.9.21

Move license info for //benchmarks/*.json into //LICENSE.

This takes the licensing information that was in
 //benchmarks/LICENSE for the //benchmarks/*.json sample files
and moves it into the top-level //LICENSE file. This will hopefully
make Google's license linter happy.
bump version to 0.9.20
Add test for json5.__version
Modify json5.tool to use __version__.

Remove legacy setup.{cfg,py} files.

Turns out I can build the package completely from stuff configured
in pyproject.toml and no longer need the setup.{cfg,py} files. The
only (very minor) drawback is that I have to duplicate the first line
of the README into the `description` field.
use `python3` for //run

Add a __version__ attribute.

Apparently `__version__` is the conventional name for a package
version (I had been using `VERSION`). This change adds __version__
but keeps VERSION around for backwards-compatibility (though I
don't know if that's actually being used).

Replace the benchmarking data files and bump version to 0.9.19.

Replaced the benchmarking data files that came from chromium.org with
three files obtained from other datasets on GitHub. Since this repo
is vendored into the chromium/src repo it was occasionally confusing
people who thought the data was actually used for non-benchmarking
purposes and thus updating it for whatever reason.

No code changes.
Update version to 0.9.18.

Add typing information. (#71)

* Add typing information.

This change takes a stab at adding typing information to the
module, in order to address #issue65.

Ideally we'd use the same typing as the builtin json module. But,
the json module has no typing information, so I've rolled my
own recursive type in `json5.ObjectType`, and the `dump` routines
take that type as input for the `obj` parameter.

Note that due to the multiple hooks the library provides, I can't
actually say much about what the `load` routines return and have
to use `Any`.

* Update to address review feedback.

This updates the PR with the feedback from richardxia@. Notably,
this switches from ObjectType to any, and removes the incorrect
`Optional[bool]`.

* remove missed `ObjectType` reference

* add py.typed

commit.message:
Switch from setup.py to pyproject.toml and update version to 0.9.17

Attempt to follow the Python Packaging guidelines and
switch from the traditional setup.py mechanism for describing
things to pyproject.toml.

I've probably messed up some things in this attempt.
Update version to 0.9.16.
Add minimal packaging instructions to //README.md.
Drop Python2 versions from setup.py.
increase version to 0.9.15

Include test files in sdist archives

Include the tests and sample file needed by them in the sdist archive,
in order to make it possible to use this archive as base of packaging
for Linux distributions (like Gentoo) and Conda.
